Trading activities on the floor of the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) yesterday commenced the trading week on a positive track, as the overall market performance indices firmed up with a gain of 0,79 per cent.
Transactions on the stock market had last Friday extended gaining streak to close on the green territory following appreciable demand by investors who are taking advantage of low prices of stocks.
FXTM Research Analyst, Mr. Lukman Otunuga, had while reacting to the current positive outlook of the local bourse, said that combination of bargain hunting and growth optimism are likely to push domestic stocks higher ahead of the presidential elections.
Otunuga who stated this in a report sent to New Telegraph, said investor optimism over government spending boosting domestic growth has continued to support appetite for risk in Nigeria with the All Share Index moving higher.
Consequently, the All-Share Index gained 251.95 basis points or 0.79 per cent to close at 31,781.87 index points as against 31.529.92 recorded last Friday, while the market capitalisation closed from N11.758 trillion at the weekend to N11.851 trillion.
Meanwhile, a turnover of 551.6 million shares exchanged in 6,231 deals was recorded in the day’s trading.The premium sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume) with 260.8 million shares exchanged by investors in 1,924 deals.
Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by the activities in the shares of Access Bank Plc and UBA Plc.
The banking sub-sector boosted by the activities in the shares of Diamond Bank Plc and Fidelity Bank Plc followed with a turnover of 150.8 million shares in 1,248 deals.
Market breadth closed positive, as Lasaco Plc led 40 gainers as against 10 losers topped by C& I Leasing Plc at the end of day’s session – an Improved performance when compared with previous outlook.